1) FILE HANDLING (CSV) — REAL-TIME SCENARIOS
Scenario 1 — Bulk Transaction Import

Problem: You receive a CSV with 1M transaction records. Some lines are malformed or have missing fields.

Concepts & Production Practices:

Use streaming read instead of readlines() to avoid memory spike.
Validate every row (trade_id, symbol, amount) before processing.
Log errors to bad_records.log without failing the entire import.
Optionally, parallelize processing using threads or asyncio if needed.

GS Interview Angle:

How to ensure data integrity? → transactional batch processing.
How to handle malformed rows? → skip, log, notify.
Scenario 2 — Real-Time Audit

Problem: Every deposit/withdrawal must be logged in CSV for auditing, but system can’t pause transactions.

Concepts:

Open CSV in append mode: a+
Use locking or atomic writes to prevent concurrent write issues.
Optionally use a buffered write to minimize disk IO, flush periodically.

GS Interview Angle:

How to handle concurrent writes? → lock, temp files, or DB for high-volume systems.
Trade-off: speed vs consistency.
Scenario 3 — Large File Processing

Problem: Read a 10GB CSV of historical trades to calculate moving averages.

Concepts:

Chunked reading using itertools.islice or pandas.read_csv(..., chunksize=...)
Avoid loading all data into memory.
Use generator functions to process line by line.

GS Interview Angle:

Memory management: generators vs full read.
Error handling: corrupt lines, inconsistent types.
